docs.abstract: A trove of images were found in a photographer’s family home. Now they are part of an exhibition opening next week in Harlem that captures pivotal years in the Black Panther Party.
docs.snippet: A trove of images were found in a photographer’s family home. Now they are part of an exhibition opening next week in Harlem that captures pivotal years in the Black Panther Party.
docs.lead_paragraph: Not long after his mother passed away in 2018, a massive relic from Jeffrey Henson Scales’ childhood was unexpectedly found in his family’s home. His stepfather and older brother were preparing the house for an eventual sale when they came across a trove of 40 rolls of film.

headline.main: How a Surprise Discovery of Photographs From the 1960s Meets the Moment

docs.abstract: America needs safer streets, not empty slogans.
docs.snippet: America needs safer streets, not empty slogans.
docs.lead_paragraph: In Harlem last Sunday, a woman named Shanice Young was returning from her baby shower when she was shot in the head, allegedly by her ex-boyfriend. The ex was apparently looking to confront her current boyfriend when, instead, he shot her.

docs.abstract: The “Golden Coach,” built for Queen Wilhelmina of Holland in 1896, is emerging as a new focus of debate over slavery, colonialist oppression and history.
docs.snippet: The “Golden Coach,” built for Queen Wilhelmina of Holland in 1896, is emerging as a new focus of debate over slavery, colonialist oppression and history.
docs.lead_paragraph: AMSTERDAM — In 1896, the city of Amsterdam decided to build Queen Wilhelmina a very special gift: a carriage covered in gold. The “Golden Coach” was designed to represent the entire kingdom and its resources, with leather from Brabant, cushions filled with flax from Zeeland and teak from the Dutch colony of Java.

headline.main: Colonial-Era Royal Carriage Stirs Up Modern Backlash in Netherlands
headline.print_headline: Dutch King’s Gold Coach, Reminder of Colonial Past, Incites a Modern Backlash

docs.abstract: A rally scheduled for Saturday in Washington is intended to continue a Republican effort to rewrite the narrative of the assault on the Capitol. The facts undercut their assertions.
docs.snippet: A rally scheduled for Saturday in Washington is intended to continue a Republican effort to rewrite the narrative of the assault on the Capitol. The facts undercut their assertions.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the eight months since a pro-Trump mob stormed the Capitol, some Republicans have tried to build a case — belied by the facts — that the vast federal investigation of the riot has been essentially unfair, its targets the victims of political persecution.

headline.main: Debunking the Pro-Trump Right’s Claims About the Jan. 6 Riot
headline.print_headline: Misunderstood Tourists? ‘Political Hostages’? No. Debunking Riot Claims.

docs.abstract: Last summer’s racial reckoning brought calls for an industrywide overhaul in fashion. But change is slow.
docs.snippet: Last summer’s racial reckoning brought calls for an industrywide overhaul in fashion. But change is slow.
docs.lead_paragraph: On the last Friday morning in August, the website for Harper’s Bazaar magazine led with an image of a Black model smiling widely in an Hermès gown, her hair in dreadlocks. Beneath that was a portrait of Lil Nas X and, just below it, an assemblage of stories about Aaliyah’s personal style.

headline.main: At Top Magazines, Black Representation Remains a Work in Progress

docs.lead_paragraph: A U.S. government advisory panel has recommended booster shots of the Pfizer-BioNTech Covid vaccine for adults over 65, for people ages 18 to 64 with underlying conditions and for residents of long-term-care homes, but it declined to endorse additional doses for workers who might have higher exposure on the job.

docs.abstract: According to a transcript released Friday, a member of the Minnesota State Patrol said there was “a purge of emails and text messages” after troopers responded to protests in Minneapolis last year.
docs.snippet: According to a transcript released Friday, a member of the Minnesota State Patrol said there was “a purge of emails and text messages” after troopers responded to protests in Minneapolis last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Minnesota State Patrol troopers deleted text messages and emails shortly after responding to protests that erupted over the police killing of George Floyd in Minneapolis last year, according to a major who testified in federal court in July.

headline.main: Minnesota Troopers Deleted Texts and Emails After Floyd Protests, Major Testifies

docs.abstract: Fifty years ago, 18- to 20-year-olds were guaranteed the right to vote. This teaching resource uses primary sources to help students explore the history and significance of this important expansion of voting rights.
docs.snippet: Fifty years ago, 18- to 20-year-olds were guaranteed the right to vote. This teaching resource uses primary sources to help students explore the history and significance of this important expansion of voting rights.
docs.lead_paragraph: Note to our audience: Most of our Lessons of the Day include warm-up activities, critical thinking questions and going-further activities that are written directly to students. Occasionally, however, we create a more in-depth exploration of a particular theme intended to inspire teachers, as we have done here. Have a look and tell us what you think!

headline.main: Teaching the 26th Amendment With The New York Times
